S3.T2.caption: Table 2: Scenarios for simulated data.
references: The analyses with simulated data have two main objectives: investigating the efficiency of Bayesian network estimation using the algorithm of Goudie and Mukherjee, (2016) and, primarily, analyzing the efficiency of the proposed methodology to generated and analyze synthetic data. To do that, various scenarios are considered in terms of the number of variables, sample size and prior distribution of the network. The true values of the respective parameters θ𝜃\theta vary between 0.2 and 0.8. For each scenario determined by these factors, 10 replications (datasets) are generated. The simulated scenarios are described in Table 2.

The uniform prior on the network corresponds to the prior in (5) with γ=0𝛾0\gamma=0. Since the networks in Table 2 are considerably simpler than the complete one, it is expected that, starting from γ=0𝛾0\gamma=0, the posterior probability of the true network increases as the value of γ𝛾\gamma does. In this sense, the calibration of this hyperparameter will be done by seeking the smallest value of γ𝛾\gamma for which the posterior probability of the true network exceeds 0.85.

For each of the scenarios in Table 2, 10 replications are simulated to analyze the accuracy and reliability of the results.
Uniform U​(0,1)𝑈01U(0,1) priors are adopted for the θ𝜃\theta parameters. Two prior distributions for the network are considered, an uniform (P2subscript𝑃2P_{2}) and the one proposed in (5) (P1subscript𝑃1P_{1}), with α=1𝛼1\alpha=1 and γ𝛾\gamma calibrated as explained in the previous section. These priors impact the results of methods S1subscript𝑆1S_{1} and S2subscript𝑆2S_{2}, which use the Bayesian network model. In the case of method S3subscript𝑆3S_{3}, the labels P1subscript𝑃1P_{1} and P2subscript𝑃2P_{2} in the plots refer to two replications (two sets of synthetic data) of the method.
